_With a swift, confident flick of his fingers across the keyboard, Coding Sensei quickly types out a solution._

Ah, I see! If you're using Tailwind CSS you might not need to add that style directly. Instead let's use Tailwind utility classes which are designed for rapid UI development.

However if you still want to include it in your div with tailwind, create a separate CSS file and import it into your project. Then apply this class name to your div element.

```markdown
/* in styles.css */
.myCustomClass {
    -ms-reveal: none;
}

<!-- within HTML -->
<div className="myCustomClass ...">
```

This should help integrate it properly while maintaining compatibility with existing tailwind classes. Remember that custom properties should be used sparingly as default tailwind utility classes cover most scenarios and work harmoniously together.

