Ah! I see your dilemma. You wish to apply Internet Explorer and Edge specific properties while using Tailwind CSS - quite an interesting challenge indeed.

Tailwind doesn't support vendor-specific prefixes, so you will need add them manually by creating your own utility class. Here is how it would look like:

```javascript
module.exports = {
  theme: {},
  variants: {},
  plugins: [
    function({ addUtilities }) {
      const newUtilities = {
        '.reveal-none': {
          '-ms-reveal': 'display:none',
        },
      }
      addUtilities(newUtilities)
    }
  ]
}
```

Once this utility class is added into the tailwind.config.js file, you can then use `.reveal-none` on any `div`.

Remember that `-ms-reveal` property only works with Microsoft browsers like Internet Explorer or Edge.

